<subSubSection id="629EA5B3FFACFF97FF6D47DEA2BAFECB" pageId="1" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2A3BF638FFACFF97FF6D47DEA2BAFECB" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,332]" pageId="1" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis id="18F02A2AFFACFF97FF6D47DEA708FF36" bold="true" box="[198,320,151,177]" pageId="1" pageNumber="64">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="ED848DBBFFACFF97FEE247D1A784FF36" box="[329,460,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Pyroderces" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18F02A2AFFACFF97FEE247D1A784FF36" box="[329,460,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="64">Pyroderces</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the forewing ground color varying from yellowish to reddish brown, with distinct stripes or spots. Superficially it is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="ED848DBBFFACFF97FC4A47F6A342FF5F" authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" box="[993,1290,190,216]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Anatrachyntis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18F02A2AFFACFF97FC4A47F6A2DBFF5F" box="[993,1171,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="64">Anatrachyntis</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished in males by the tegumen broad, square or rounded, somewhat bulging with a strengthening longitudinal ridge mid-dorsally; in females the signa are paired long rows of carinae or sclerotized spines. In 
<taxonomicName id="ED848DBBFFACFF97FF3C467BA773FECC" box="[151,315,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Anatrachyntis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18F02A2AFFACFF97FF3C467BA773FECC" box="[151,315,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="64">Anatrachyntis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the tegumen is long and narrow, without median ridge; and the signa are absent.
</paragraph>
